Where the investment payoff was low I was more inclined to take the selfish option, but maintained that X would be best for all.
el_questionnaire.1.player.reasons_belief: I roughly guessed the odds that they chose X given a success or failure, but was swayed a few percentages if the investment payoff was low, suspecting that the leader would be more inclined to take the safe money.  I am beginning to shift beliefs based on the previous question's point that decisions may be based on others receiving nothing given a failure, which I imagine would be a big factor in people's decisions as it was in mine.

In stage 2 I realised it was per stage.  I thought that if the leader was being selfish (especially in stage 2 and 3), they cannot lose out and therefore would be in their best interest to choose Y. However, if the outcome was successful, it was still more likely that option X was chosen due to the higher chance percentage.

el_questionnaire.1.player.comments_gener: It was a great experiment. I think it has something to do with exposing the returns and fees of  Super Funds. Whether the Super-Fund manager decides to make a costly but sure investment to the benefit of their members or a cheap but unsure investment. This can also be related to "payment for order flow" and routing trades oddly.
el_questionnaire.1.player.comments_uncle: The final payment calculation was very complicated. It made me feel like the decision has already been made in advance, that the payment will be according to Task 2, because it's easier to program that than to program paying for Task 1.    Also, I don't think I was actually matched to two other people in a group in Task 1 or to another randomly chosen person in Task 2. That it was just made for us to believe, because who's going to program all of that into the program when just making us believe that it happened is enough?
el_questionnaire.1.player.reasons_effort: I opened a new Google Sheets document, and tried to calculate the expected pay-off and variance. The ratio of the former to the latter would give me the "risk". But I didn't have enough time to code everything in, so I just looked for which one gave me more expected pay-off if I were the leader (risk-neutral).    For predicting what the leader chose, it was easy to go with Investment X probability 0 for the 250-50 and 200-0 case. For the 300-50 case, I didn't know how risk neutral the leader would be, so I had to make a gut decision there. I thought many people are more risk-averse than I am in these kinds of experiments, so I went with a gut feeling of 70%. The ideal way would be to calculate the Sharpe ratio/"risk" (expected payoff divided by variance or std deviation) and use their ratio to determine the percentage, but I didn't have time to calculate and implement that in my Google Sheets.     For predicting what the leader chose given that the investment has succeeded or given that the experiment has failed, I wanted to use Bayes' formula, but I couldn't calculate it in time, so I just did 75% * probability that I think investment X was chosen + 25% * probability that I think investment Y was chosen for part 2(a) and switch 75% and 25% for part 2(b)
el_questionnaire.1.player.reasons_belief: I described everything in a previous part of the questionnaire.

Given not much information, I had to determine which investment to choose and which amount to give. I had to question whether I should consider for myself more or other team members more. I also consider if I should go for high risk and high return for each investment.   Personally, I think it tested the trust between leader and team members. el_questionnaire.1.player.comments_gener: I enjoyed it. It made me confront my willingness to gamble odds if it's for group-mates, but not for myself. Interesting.    Although, I thought it was odd that there was a task  where we had to "predict" what the leader (who we've never met) would have chosen. And I was unsure why this probability would change whether or not the investment succeeded. Lots to think about though.
el_questionnaire.1.player.reasons_effort: I considered that Investment Y, although "riskier", was more beneficial. The lowest I could earn was about the same as the highest I would earn for Investment X. 75% is high, but it isn't extremely high. I wouldn't bet my life on those odds.     I also considered (a bit) my group-mates, and saw that they were likely to earn nothing for Investment Y. However, I (again) considered that 25% wasn't especially high, and that there was a further 50% chance my group-mates would earn money in Task 2. Ultimately, I'm not trying to justify that my choices were a bit selfish, but that given how much the outcomes for all of us are determined by 75% and 50% chances, I'd rather opt for the choice that guarantees me slightly more money

el_questionnaire.1.player.reasons_effort: The pay-off between the success of Investment X and the failure of Investment Y. Looking from a selfish perspective, for the first 2 rounds the failure of Investment Y was equal to the success of Investment X. Therefore picking Investment Y meant you would receive same or greater for the leader but not for group mates.   In the final task, where failure of Investment Y was lower than success of Investment X, I decided to pick Investment X as it would also benefit team mates not just myself.
el_questionnaire.1.player.reasons_belief: The likelihood of them picking a pay out that suited them the most.   The likelihood of them taking into consideration what others would achieve.

el_questionnaire.1.player.reasons_belief: The maximum payoff for investment X was equal to the minimum payoff for investment Y. It made no sense to pick investment X, so I was very confident that the leader picked investment Y. There was a small chance that the leader decided to be generous, but it was very unlikely, as the leader would have to act against their own interests.    If the maximum payoff for investment X exceeded the minimum payoff for investment Y, then there was a slightly greater chance of the leader picking X. The leader may see some individual benefit from picking investment X but it was still very unlikely.

Given that the 2nd investment would generally result in equal takings should the investment fail to a successful 1st investment, it would be foolish as the leader to choose the 1st investment. There was no risk for me, as I knew I would always end up with the best result if I chose the 2nd investment: even if it failed, it was still an equal result to success with the 1st investment

el_questionnaire.1.player.reasons_effort: The fact that the other members in my group would not know the decision that I have made, as well as the fact that I do not know who the other members are.
el_questionnaire.1.player.reasons_belief: I decreased the chances that the leader would choose investment x as I feel that they would realise that the members in their group would not find out what decisions that they have made & that we dont even know who is in the group. I assumed that they would have the same mindset as I do.

I answered the questions in this stage based on my own decision. For example, if I chose Investment Y without too much hesitation then I assumed that it would be a similar thought process for other participants. In Task 2, I simply split the endowment equally as I value fairness and think that the other participant would also split it equally.
el_questionnaire.1.player.reasons_effort: Mainly my own personal gain but also considered the degree of inequality that would be created between me and the other participants were the investment to fail.
el_questionnaire.1.player.reasons_belief: My own decision-making process. I also believe that most people will choose Investment Y as it provides the best outcome for the leader overall. Finally, the outcome does not change my initial prediction so I chose the same likelihood in both parts of the question.

el_questionnaire.1.player.reasons_belief: Again, I considered how likely it was that the investment would succeed or fail. I also considered how much they would earn with these different outcomes. I didn't consider how much we (the members) would earn as much when making these predictions.
